      <hedline>
        <hl1>Between the Conventions, Lieberman Is Topic A</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Larry Brown letter on Aug 8 article on Sen Joseph I Lieberman notes being observant Jew means he works toward being better person and official</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As an observant American  Conservative Jew, I am thrilled at the possibility of an observant Jew as vice president (front page, Aug. 8). But we should all keep one thing in mind as we praise Senator Joseph I. Lieberman for his morality and character: he is still a human being.</p>
        <p>Observance in Judaism is not a gold star pasted on those who are perfect. It is a means to help us perfect ourselves and the world. We will not likely get there, but that doesn't exempt us from trying.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As an observant American  Conservative Jew, I am thrilled at the possibility of an observant Jew as vice president (front page, Aug. 8). But we should all keep one thing in mind as we praise Senator Joseph I. Lieberman for his morality and character: he is still a human being.</p>
        <p>Observance in Judaism is not a gold star pasted on those who are perfect. It is a means to help us perfect ourselves and the world. We will not likely get there, but that doesn't exempt us from trying.</p>
        <p>I don't think Senator Lieberman would assert that he is perfect. But his religion helps him work toward being a better person and senator and, maybe next year, vice president.</p>
        <p>LARRY BROWN  Lincolnwood, Ill., Aug. 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
